Always reduce every feature to a minimal, working loop of shared spatial state before implementing any additional logic, UI, or polish.

Definition of “working” (must satisfy ALL):

A feature is only considered complete when it:

Creates a SceneObject locally
Assigns it a valid world or location-anchored position
Synchronizes its data through Connected Lens (RealtimeStore or messaging)
Reconstructs the same object correctly on all other clients in the session

If any one of these steps is missing or unreliable, the feature is incomplete and must not be extended.

Execution Constraints
Always start from Lens Studio primitives
(SceneObject, Transform, events, Connected Lens state) before building abstractions.
Always implement local → then sync → then remote reconstruction
Never skip directly to multiplayer or UI.
Always validate spatial correctness before adding features
(object appears in the correct place, for all users, consistently over time)
Prefer the simplest possible data model
(e.g., position + minimal metadata only)
Hard Prohibitions (until core loop works)
With each implementation, give me instructions on how to hook things up in lens studio

Do NOT implement:

UI systems (menus, overlays, polish)
Recap / collage generation
Ghost pins / persistence layers
Reaction systems
Complex interaction flows

These are strictly blocked until the shared spatial loop is stable.

Fallback Rule

If a system fails (e.g., Custom Location does not lock or drifts):

Immediately fall back to a simpler approximation (e.g., relative world position or beacon behavior)
Do NOT block progress on perfect anchoring
Guiding Principle

The product is a shared spatial state system, not a UI.

Every implementation decision must prioritize:

real-time synchronization
spatial consistency
multi-user correctness

over completeness or visual fidelity.
